Day 26 - 5 days left until the end, 120 hours remain...

Good evening soldiers! I apologize for missing yesterday's rollcall, I ended up sleeping through rollcall but I'm here now! I remember someone mentioning that you are able to count the days with a singular hand now, which I find quite interesting so I encourage you all to do the same! Here's a tip for a job well done!

- If you ever feel down on your luck on NNN, I find it's very helpful to listen to motivating music! Personally, I've been listening to Undefeatable from the Sonic Frontiers OST. Tbf that game has a lot of really good motivational music, but there's something special about Undefeatable and Find Your Flame and I'm curious if anyone else feels the same way.

Today was rather rough for me, even though I never even edged I still feel like today was the closest I got to losing. Still, now that we can count the days with a single hand, I feel like that's going to make the long haul feel much shorter.

The next few days are going to be the toughest we've all ever faced, but if we've made it this far then at this point, why turn back now? Stay on your toes soldiers, and feel free to vent about how awesome / horrible your NNN is going right here, I'd love to hear all about it. Thanks for the support soldiers! I don't know if I could've done this without you, salute! o7

Capt. Hector's Log book. November 26th, 1887:

Rich deep fresh green of infinite depths and tints. If secrets had a colour, it would be this. It baffles and delights the eye. A chilly wind brushes me. I have reach The Emerald Vista. SOMETHING SOUGHT, the voice intones. SOMETHING LOST.

I peer into the depths and surrender my understanding to the wind. There are changes which will wash away all that I am and all that I will be. Nothing is familiar. Everything is new as morning. My sight is dazzled, my perceptions confounded. Yet again, something was taken from me: sight.

The doors opened once more. A narrow space of blinding light, all colours and none, between the towers of Brite and the towers of Teneb. I walk onto The Diamond Bridge. Once there, I will be exposed, like an insect in the desert, like a fresh carcass on the operating table, like a jewel in the sun.

I tried to remember the Sun, or at least tales of Vision of the Surface. Stories of those who has glimpse at the real Sun, how the light sears its blasphemous knowledge onto them, how zailors went mad by the light and the law that follows. And it works.

I cross the bridge to The Iridescence.

I prayed to Salt, Storm, and Stone that I will survive this voyage, for the deep dark zee is unforgiving.
